messages.content:
Using the Gibbs free energies provided by the workers, we can calculate the Gibbs free energy change (ΔG) for the reaction.

The reaction is: 1 (Ethene) + 1 (Water) -> 1 (Ethanol)

The Gibbs free energy change (ΔG) is calculated as:

ΔG = Σ G_products - Σ G_reactants

Where G represents the Gibbs free energy of the substance.

Substituting the values we have:

ΔG = G(Ethanol) - [G(Ethene) + G(Water)]
   = -46.47441112785896 - [-31.469241474976236 + (-14.50370329271722)]
   = -46.47441112785896 - (-45.972944767693456)
   = -0.501466360165504

So, the Gibbs free energy change (ΔG) for the reaction at 500K is approximately -0.501 eV.
